[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"],["Pagebanner default.jpg"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.caraquet.ca Caraquet"]}]}," is a small (pop 4000) francophone village on the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Acadian Coast"]]}," of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["New Brunswick"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\nMuch of what is now ",{"type":"[[","value":[["New Brunswick"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nova Scotia"]]}," was once Acadia, a French-speaking colony in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["North America"]]}," which was defeated by the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["England"],["English"]]}," in the 1750's. ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Great Britain"]]}," demanded Acadia pledge allegiance; the Acadians refused out of fear they would be forced to attack la ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Québec"],["Nouvelle France"]]}," on behalf of the English and claimed neutrality. The English retaliated with mass deportations, known as ",{"type":"''","value":["le grand dérangement de 1755"]},". Some Acadians settled as far afield as ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Louisiana"]]},", some returned to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["France"]]},". A few, displaced from points in southern New Brunswick such as ",{"type":"''","value":["Fort Beauséjour"]},", fled north to establish the clandestine precursors of what is now Caraquet in 1757.\n\nCaraquet is primarily a lobster fishing village and seaport on the Baie des Chaleurs, a warm bay which separates New Brunswick from Québec's ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Gaspé"]]}," region. Tourists tend to arrive in number from Québec in July and early August, with crowds peaking during the August 15 Acadian \"fête nationale\". After the festival, the crowds leave and life in this tiny francophone corner of New Brunswick peacefully returns to normal.\n\nCaraquet is home to the province's only French-language daily newspaper, the independent ",{"type":"''","value":["Acadie Nouvelle"]},".\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\nFrom ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bathurst (New Brunswick)"]]},", follow NB route 11 by motorcar.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get around"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["See"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=Musée Acadien de Caraquet"],["alt="],["url=http:\/\/www.museecaraquet.ca"],["email="],["address=15, boul. St-Pierre Est"],["lat="],["long="],["directions="],["phone=+1 506 726-2682"],["tollfree="],["fax=+1 506 726-2660"],["hours=10AM-6PM June-Sep, 10AM-8PM Jul-Aug. Sundays 1-6PM."],["price="],["content="]]}]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=Village Historique Acadien"],["alt="],["wikipedia=Village Historique Acadien"],["url=http:\/\/www.villagehistoriqueacadien.com"],["email="],["address=5, rue du Pont, Bertrand NB"],["lat="],["long="],["directions="],["phone=+1 506 726-2600"],["tollfree=+1-877-721-2200"],["fax=+1 506 726-2601"],["hours=10AM-6PM daily, early June-mid Sept"],["price=$17.50"],["content=A pioneer village living museum reconstructing a francophone village of 1755-1855 with its people. Château Albert hotel with bar and restaurant on-site."]]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Do"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["do"],["name=Cinéma du Centre"],["alt="],["url=http:\/\/www.cinemaducentre.ca"],["email="],["address=220, boulevard Saint-Pierre Ouest"],["lat="],["long="],["directions="],["phone=+1 506 726-3456"],["tollfree="],["fax="],["hours="],["price="],["content=(726-FILM) Downtown cinema with a mix of French and English-language films."]]}]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["do"],["name=Théâtre populaire d'Acadie"],["alt="],["url="],["email="],["address="],["lat="],["long="],["directions="],["phone="],["tollfree="],["fax="],["hours="],["price="],["content=French-language professional summer theatre at the Boîte-Théâtre."]]}]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["Events"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["do"],["name=Festival Acadien"],["alt="],[